e enslavers of the past and present in place of white Americans and Europeans. Doing so, Beutin contends, creates a rhetorical defense against being held liable for slavery’s dispossessions and violence. Despite these implications, Beutin demonstrates that antitrafficking discourse remains popular and politically useful for former slaving nations and their racial beneficiaries because it refashions historic justifications for white supremacy into today’s abolition of slavery.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aHuman trafficking. 0aRacism against Black people. 0aRacism in mass media. 0aSlavery in mass media. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Black Studies (Global).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311099775040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478024354?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478024354423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478024354/original  a978-3-11-099775-0  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles